title: For Sale:  1943 Remington Rand M1911 A1 US ARMY Type II
postcontent:
1943 Remington Rand M1911 A1 US ARMY Type II

This is a early Du-Lite blue Remington Rand with type 2 slide, early ring less grips, checkered small parts, and Colt barrel. This pistol is an all original example, and even includes the original holster and issued ammunition! This pistol has all of it's original parts and is the correct configuration, with original finish. This is a rare early Remington Rand in the 930000 serial number range. Notice the raised grips screws, this was common on early examples. The identifying characteristic of a Type II is the Remington Rand, Inc. spans the length of the slide stop, while on the Type III slides it only runs 70% of the length and on Type I Remington Rand legend New York is not abbreviated.

I'm asking $2750 OBO for the pistol, holster and ammunition, shipped and insured to your FFL, or face to face in Colorado.

title: For Sale:  Buckmaster LT Knife (Buck 185) -RARE-
postcontent:
I have up for sale, a rare Buck knife. This is the Buckmaster LT (Buck 185). This is a skeleton handle version of the famous Buckmaster knife. There were only 6038 of these knives made between 1984 and 1989. To put this in perspective, if this knife were a car, it would be something like a Plymouth Superbird as the numbers that were produced are not that far apart. This knife is in very good condition with some minor wear from use, and it has a small nick in the rubber handle (see photo), otherwise it is in fine shape. Look this up online if you like and you will find that in almost any condition they are fetching a high price (around three hundred). You can have mine for 150.00. If your a collector of knives, this is one you don't want to miss out on, as there will never be any more made, and the stock of what is out there will only get slimmer as time goes on. Many of these knives have already been lost due to hard use, as few understood how rare they are. This is a survival knife after all, that is what it was designed for, and what I used it for when I went camping, until it got stored away years ago, and getting stored away is why it's still in nice shape. If your interested let me know, until then the Buckmaster will be going back into storage. Thanks.

NOTE: This is for local pick up only, I will not ship this knife. Thanks.

For an extra $200 I can include a matching Deerslayer 20" rifled barrel with iron sights that is in 99% condition. This shotgun has been carefully maintained and stored.  It has the corncob forend.

I will sell this gun for $650 with either barrel. Your choice.  

 It only takes a minute or two to change the barrel with no tools--wonderful for cleaning, storage, and transporting.  The lockup on the barrel to the receiver is much tighter on Ithacas since it's a threaded fit, not merely a slip fit.

I prefer not to ship this shotgun and would like a face-to-face transfer with proper Florida ID exchange and Bill of Sale signed by both parties.  If you see this ad then the gun is still available.   Please don't ask if it is still available.  

The Ithaca 87 is just like the Ithaca 37 except it has no slam fire trigger.  The barrels will even fit most Ithaca 37's with serial numbers of 855,000 or greater.  Thank for looking!

title: For Sale:  Colt-Sharps Rifle in 7mm Rem Magnum (Rare Rifle!!)
location: Western Platte County, Missouri, Missouri, United States
postcontent:
Pretty rare rifle... hit a few sites and search for a Colt-Sharps and you'll see what I mean by rare. I believe something less than 500 were made...I've heard 477.  Of this very few were made in 7mm Remington magnum. Now the rifle in the pics has a Zeiss 3-12X56 scope with 30mm tube. Scope is not included.  If you really want, add $1300... Scope's not included, but the mounts are. The rifle is in excellent condition. Any questions will be quickly answered. Is my price flexible? Does that mean I'll entertain an offer? Send it along...I'll consider...but this is a rifle that if you buy and keep it in it's present condition, it'll continue to appreciate.  Put out in the 1970s, the rifle was way ahead of its time.  Single shot rifles had not yet come into vogue and the cost was 3 times plus back then of a Ruger #1... Sooo, it never established a market and now it's a shootable collectible. 

Rob
US Army (Ret)
